WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:02.695
Well, this is one of the improvements.

00:03.396 --> 00:05.398
And that already helps a lot.

00:05.499 --> 00:07.762
But then they run into a problem.

00:07.822 --> 00:10.726
And this is not necessarily a problem with their method.

00:11.066 --> 00:15.212
But this is a problem in general, when you use relative positioning codings.

00:15.232 --> 00:24.705
So they say, given a sentence, a new store opened beside a new mall, right, that's a sentence, the words, store and mall,

00:24.685 --> 00:28.930
Let's say you do this mask language model pre-training.

00:29.270 --> 00:34.096
You mask out the words store and mall and you ask the model to reconstruct them.

00:35.198 --> 00:37.560
Using only the local context, e.g.

00:37.600 --> 00:43.728
relative position and surrounding words is insufficient for the model to distinguish store and mall in this sentence.

00:44.108 --> 00:47.352
Since both follow the word new,

00:47.332 --> 00:49.454
with the same relative positions.

00:49.474 --> 00:53.979
So from the word new, you know, relatively, it's always plus one.

00:54.320 --> 00:55.761
Oopsie.

00:55.781 --> 00:58.364
It's plus one to this word.

00:58.745 --> 01:00.967
So the model cannot distinguish the two.

01:01.368 --> 01:11.719
So there is a need for absolute position encodings, because if you had absolute position encodings, you could maybe make sense, though.

01:11.699 --> 01:29.202
Since you could figure out like store is probably kind of a smaller thing and mall is kind of a bigger thing, so it's more likely that the store opened beside the new mall than the mall opened beside the new store.

01:29.182 --> 01:34.248
So that means we need absolute positioning coatings or something like this, right?

01:34.728 --> 01:51.186
And especially we could have relative positioning coatings, but if this is a very long sentence and we truncate them somewhere, again, these two things are not in range of one another, and they're not going to know how far, you know, they are apart and each one by itself is just plus one apart.

01:52.007 --> 01:52.928
So

01:52.908 --> 01:54.932
How do we solve the problem?

01:55.372 --> 01:57.616
We feed in absolute positioning coatings.

01:57.977 --> 02:00.441
However, that's exactly what they criticize.

02:00.481 --> 02:05.170
They say, no, relative positioning coatings are much better than absolute for learning.

02:05.791 --> 02:17.211
And that's kind of the same reasoning why a convolution is better than a fully connected layer because you kind of slide the transformation over and it's simply data relative to each other.

02:17.191 --> 02:28.245
So relative positioning makes a lot of sense if when every word can do computation, not based on where exactly it is in the sentence, but how it is in relation to other words.

02:28.386 --> 02:37.157
Otherwise, if you have absolute positioning codings, what you would have to do is you would have to say, well, if I'm the word am, and I'm in position two,

02:37.137 --> 02:39.599
I need to learn to attend to position three.

02:40.060 --> 02:44.544
However, if I'm the word am and I'm in position three, I need to learn to attend to position four.

02:44.924 --> 02:47.987
And if I'm in position four, I need to learn to attend in position five.

02:48.027 --> 02:49.808
These are all different things you need to learn.

02:50.489 --> 02:57.716
However, if you have relative encoding, what you can do is you can simply say, I want to attend to the word that's right after me.

02:58.536 --> 02:58.797
Easy.

02:59.657 --> 03:05.963
But we do need absolute position encoding for some things, namely disambiguate between tasks like this.

03:05.943 --> 03:14.309
So they feed in absolute position information, but instead of doing it the beginning, they do it at the end.

03:14.690 --> 03:18.422
So at the beginning, we have the word vectors, right?

03:18.482 --> 03:19.345
They go in here.

03:20.708 --> 03:22.732
And then we have position information.

03:23.774 --> 03:25.377
One, two, three, four, five.

03:25.737 --> 03:29.545
We have that at every single layer of the transformer.

03:29.585 --> 03:32.009
We feed it in again and again and again.

03:32.450 --> 03:34.634
We feed in the same P vectors.

03:35.195 --> 03:39.844
They have different of these transformations in each layer.

03:40.665 --> 03:44.252
So the actual transformation that makes the keys and the values

03:44.232 --> 03:57.604
Sorry, the keys and the queries of the positional information are different, but the vectors are the same every time and then at the very top So these are p relative So this is sorry.

03:57.704 --> 03:58.565
Yeah, I mixed up.

03:58.605 --> 04:13.058
This is the this is this negative 2 negative 1 0 1 2 for the middle token and then at the end we're going to feed in Absolute position encodings so here we have you know your

04:13.038 --> 04:14.663
Let's start at one.

04:14.883 --> 04:16.247
Let's be good math lab people.

04:17.732 --> 04:24.551
Here we have 12345 that we're going to now combine with the vectors that come out of here.

04:26.317 --> 04:27.520
So the reasoning is

04:29.879 --> 04:34.506
They say there are two methods of incorporating absolute position.

04:34.807 --> 04:37.771
The BERT model incorporates absolute position in the input layer.

04:38.352 --> 04:46.765
In dBERT, we incorporate them right after all the transformer layers, but before the softmax layer for mask token prediction, as shown in Figure 2.

04:47.206 --> 04:50.571
I've looked at Figure 2, it's not really helpful, honestly.

04:50.551 --> 05:10.614
So that is this figure in the appendix, where they say, okay, so in the BERT, in the BERT, you have the absolute positioning coding somewhere down here, it goes through all the transformer layers, and then you have this classification layer at the top that does the language model decoding.

05:11.094 --> 05:17.301
However, in their model, what you'd have is you have all the transformer layers here, down here,

05:17.281 --> 05:22.987
And then you have the absolute position encodings that come in through the side here.

05:23.768 --> 05:35.962
And kind of the last transformer layer now has access to these absolute layers or the last N. I think N in their case is two or one, one or two.

05:36.582 --> 05:47.254
So in the last layer or the last layers, now the transformer has access to the absolute positions and before it's just relative position at each step.

05:47.234 --> 05:56.668
And the reason that that helps, because the transformer part learns to deal with relative positions.

05:58.470 --> 06:09.226
In this way, they say here, deberta captures the relative positions in all the transformer layers and only uses the absolute position that's complementary information when decoding the masked words.

06:09.686 --> 06:14.473
Thus we call deberta's decoding component an enhanced masked decoder.

06:14.453 --> 06:19.400
and they compare the two and they observed that EMD works much better.

06:19.881 --> 06:25.168
So feeding absolute positions at the end works better than feeding them at the beginning.

06:28.292 --> 06:37.305
We conjecture that the early incorporation of absolute positions used by Bert might undesirably hamper the model from learning sufficient information of relative position.

06:37.285 --> 06:43.233
In addition, EMD also enables us to introduce other useful information that is in two positions.

06:43.274 --> 06:44.459
We leave it for future work.

06:44.479 --> 06:46.549
So they say you could also feed in other information.

06:46.610 --> 06:50.046
I guess that's the case in every single neural network ever.

